The Kenya Sevens Rugby team saved themselves some blushes as they came from a 19-0 down to beat Chile 26-19 in the final group A match of the Vancouver Sevens. It was their only win in the group.Chile started very well by scoring three tries before Collins Injera reduced the deficit as the opponents, a noncore side, led 19-7 at breather. But they failed to hold on as Kenya mounted a serious challenge in the second half to add three more tries through Eden Agero, Frank Wanyama and Sammy Oliech.The win saw the national side book a quarter final place against Scotland in the challenge trophy cup. Kenya is without Billy Odhiambo who picked a knock during the Las Vegas Sevens where they won the challenge trophy.Earlier on, the national side had lost 28-14 against England and 15-5 against South Africa to end their hopes of reaching main cup quarters for the first time since Capet Town Sevens.In the match against England, Kenya started by defending well and finally found break through Willy Ambaka following brilliant play by Eden Agero. However, England leveled the scores before half time, courtesy of Phil Burgess after turning over the ball at their twenty two.The second half looked promising for Kenya as Sammy Oliech restored Kenya s lead with Eden Agero adding the extras. But Kenya collapsed once again as England were awarded a penalty try and Willy Ambaka sin binned for infringement.England were then in control as they added two more tries to take the game beyond Kenya's reach. The next match against key rivals South Africa was a must-win for the boys but they once again failed to secure the much needed win and keep alive hopes of a quarter final places.Danger man Rosco Specman picked from where he left during the las Vegas sevens as he danced past Kenya's defence to give the Blitzbokke a 5-0 lead. Ruhan Nel gave them a 10-0 lead at half time as South Africa remained firmly in control.Kenya reduced the deficit to 10-7 through Bush Mwale but hopes of causing an upset were dashed, as the series leaders added the third try through Chris Dry, to win the match 15-5 and qualify for the quarter finals.